Protocol Description	Placental/decidual blocks are derived from historical samples of first trimester hysterectomies, which include the site of placentation, the entire uterus containing the placenta, decidua and myometrium.    Tissue samples used for this study were obtained with written informed consent from all participants in accordance with the guidelines in The Declaration of Helsinki 2000. Site of collection was at the Addenbooke’s Hospital (Cambridge, UK) under ethical approval from the Cambridge Local Research Ethics Committee (04/Q0108/23), which is incorporated into the overarching ethics permission given to the Centre for Trophoblast Research biobank for the “Biology of the Human Uterus in Pregnancy and Disease Tissue Bank” at the University of Cambridge under ethical approval from the East of England-Cambridge Central Research Ethics Committee (17/EE/0151) and from the London-Hampstead Research Ethics Committee (20/LO/0115).	For 10x Genomics Visium library preparation, ten micron cryosections were cut and placed on Visium slides, then processed according to the manufacturer’s instructions. Sections were fixed with cold methanol, stained with haematoxylin and eosin and imaged on a Hamamatsu NanoZoomer S60 before permeabilisation, reverse transcription and cDNA synthesis using a template-switching protocol. Second-strand cDNA was liberated from the slide.	Single-indexed libraries were prepared using the 10x Genomics PCR-based protocol.	Libraries were sequenced (1 per lane on a HiSeq4000), aiming for 300M raw reads per sample, with the following sequencing format; read 1: 28 cycles, i7 index: 8 cycles, i5 index: 0 cycles and read 2: 91 cycles.	Visium data was analysed using the 10x software Space Ranger v1.1.0 with 10x genome GRCh38-3_0_0 as reference. All parameters where set to default.
